## Root cause
`weave/trace/op_protocol.py`'s `Op(Protocol[P, R]).__call__` had TWO overloads:
    @overload
    def __call__(self, *args: P.args, **kwargs: P.kwargs) -> R: ...   # typed
    @overload
    def __call__(self, *args: Any, **kwargs: Any) -> Any: ...         # catch-all
Type checkers evaluate overloads in order; when a call doesn't match the typed first
overload (wrong type, missing/extra arg) they SILENTLY fall through to the catch-all,
which accepts anything and returns Any -> no error. PR #4305 had added the typed
overload (so the RETURN type R was preserved and that part of #4305 worked) but the
catch-all kept ARGUMENT checking disabled. That is the residual bug the commenter saw.

## The fix
Delete the catch-all overload, leaving a single typed `__call__`. `overload` is still
used by `__get__`; `Any` still used elsewhere — no unused imports.

## Actions / investigation
- Read op.py (the `op()` decorator: returns `Op[P, R]`, wrapper carries P.args/P.kwargs)
  and op_protocol.py (the Protocol).
- git-archaeology: catch-all introduced when the protocol moved to its own file
  (a086f1b09b); the generic `Op[P,R]` + typed overload came from PR #4305 (45bae73fc8).
  No git notes on either (predate the convention). #4305's test only checked runtime
  `inspect.signature`/`get_type_hints` — which is exactly why the static-checking
  regression was never caught.
- Built an isolated pyright harness (.context/, gitignored) and a minimal Protocol
  repro to confirm behavior.

## Errors & Mistakes (the big one)
- MAJOR early confusion: removing the catch-all and running `uvx pyright .context/repro.py`
  showed 0 errors -> I briefly concluded the catch-all wasn't the cause. WRONG. The repo's
  [tool.pyright] config sets `reportCallIssue = false` and `reportArgumentType = false`
  and excludes tests/. So pyright-from-repo-root SUPPRESSES exactly the errors I was
  testing for. Once I ran pyright with an isolated `typeCheckingMode: basic` config, the
  truth appeared: removing the catch-all DOES restore arg checking. Sanity-check your
  checker config before trusting "0 errors".
- pyright `--project`/`-p` is REQUIRED for it to apply a config's extraPaths; passing a
  bare file path resolves no imports and reports nothing (another "0 errors" red herring).

## Verification
- Isolated pyright (basic mode) + mypy both: missing arg -> reportCallIssue/[call-arg];
  wrong type -> reportArgumentType/[arg-type]; return type preserved; .call/.calls,
  attribute access, bare/untyped Op (P defaults to ...), dynamic op(*args,**kwargs)
  unpacking, and Callable[...,Any] compat all still pass.
- No internal regressions: pyright over all of weave/ = 254 errors before AND after
  (0 new). mypy (repo config) over weave/flow+scorers+trace = 84 before AND after (empty
  diff).
- Runtime: 145+ op tests pass (test_op_decorator_behaviour, _call_method, _coroutines,
  _generators, _return_forms, _versioning, _accumulator, _argument_forms, anonymous_ops).

## Regression test design (tests/trace/test_op_static_typing.py)
- Shells out to a type checker on a generated snippet and asserts the bad calls are
  flagged. Chose mypy over pyright: pure-Python, deterministic, no node binary to
  download, already a repo pre-commit tool. (pyright needs node + a network download ->
  flaky in CI.)
- Uses `--follow-imports=silent` so mypy resolves weave's real `Op` type but suppresses
  diagnostics inside weave. Isolated mypy.ini + `--cache-dir` into tmp so nothing leaks
  into the repo.
- SELF-VALIDATES: a plain (non-op) bad call must be flagged; if not, the harness is
  misconfigured and the test SKIPS rather than false-failing. Also skips if mypy can't
  launch (offline / shard without it).
- Verified it FAILS with the catch-all restored and PASSES without it, on both mypy 2.1.0
  and the locked 1.20.2.
- Consulted Codex (per CLAUDE.md dependency rule): endorsed removing the catch-all as
  correct+complete and endorsed making it a real CI gate (mypy dep), kept narrow+documented.

## Hints for Future Agents
- Don't "simplify" `__call__` back to a catch-all or `Callable[..., Any]` — that silently
  disables arg checking for every op. The single typed signature is load-bearing.
- If you must let an op be called with arbitrary args, widen at the call site
  (annotate `Op[..., Any]` / bare `Op` / `Callable[..., Any]`), not the protocol globally.
- The new test is skip-safe by design; it only becomes a CI gate once mypy is a test dep
  (PR2 of this stack).

